   229‚Üí * Potential for optimization here:
   230‚Üí *
   231‚Üí * Since DeepExclude distributes the union of the input type, it can
   232‚Üí * generate very large union types on patterns touching several unions at once.
   233‚Üí * If we were sorting patterns from those which distribute the smallest
   234‚Üí * amount of union types to those which distribute the largest, we would eliminate
   235‚Üí * cheap cases more quickly and have less cases in the input type for patterns
   236‚Üí * that will be expensive to exclude.
   237‚Üí *
   238‚Üí * This pre supposes that we have a cheap way of telling if the number
   239‚Üí * of union types a pattern touches and a cheap way of sorting the tuple
   240‚Üí * of patterns.
   241‚Üí * - For the first part, we could reuse `FindMatchingUnions` and pick the `length`
   242‚Üí *   of the returned tuple.
   243‚Üí * - For the second part though I'm not aware a cheap way of sorting a tuple.
   245‚Üítype DeepExcludeAll<a, tupleList extends any[]> = [a] extends [never]
   246‚Üí  ? never
   247‚Üí  : tupleList extends [infer excluded, ...infer tail]
   248‚Üí  ? DeepExcludeAll<DeepExclude<a, excluded>, tail>
   249‚Üí  : a;
